  "prompt": "What prove the existence of the boundary between the crust and the mantle?",
  "response": "The boundary between the Earth's crust and the mantle is known as the **Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 discontinuity** (or **Moho** for short). Its existence was first proven in 1909 by Croatian seismologist **Andrija Mohorovi\u010di\u0107**, who observed that seismic waves from earthquakes traveled at different speeds as they passed through layers of the Earth. Here's why the Moho is considered evidence of the crust-mantle boundary:\n\n### Evidence for the Moho:\n1. **Seismic Wave Velocity Change**:\n   - Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 noticed that **P-waves** (primary seismic waves) and **S-waves** (secondary seismic waves) abruptly increased in speed at a certain depth.\n   - This sudden increase in velocity indicated a change in the density and composition of the material, suggesting a transition from the crust to the mantle.\n\n2. **Density and Composition**:\n   - The crust is made of lighter rocks (e.g., granite in the continental crust and basalt in the oceanic crust), while the mantle consists of denser, ultramafic rocks like peridotite.\n   - The Moho marks the boundary where these two distinct layers meet.\n\n3. **Reflection and Refraction**:\n   - Seismic waves reflect and refract at the Moho, providing further evidence of the boundary.\n   - Scientists use these reflections and refractions to map the depth of the Moho globally.\n\n4. **Drilling and Sampling**:\n   - While the Moho itself has not been directly drilled, projects like the **Deep Sea Drilling Project** and **Integrated Ocean Drilling Program** have sampled the oceanic crust and uppermost mantle, supporting the idea of a distinct boundary.\n\n### Depth of the Moho:\n- The Moho lies at an average depth of **35 km** beneath continents and **5-10 km** beneath oceanic crust, reflecting the differences in crustal thickness.\n\nIn summary, the Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 discontinuity is a well-established boundary proven by seismic data, density differences, and the composition of rocks, marking the transition from the Earth's crust to the mantle.",
